It’s #CatalogToKitchen and in honor of Korean Family Month, Samantha made Kimchi Stew 김치찌개 and Garlicky Cooked Soybean Sprouts 콩나물무침 from Maangchi’s 2019 Maangchi’s Big Book of Korean Cooking: From Everyday Meals to Celebration Cuisine. Borrow the book: https://find.minlib.net/iii/encore/record/C__Rb3857254:=:https://find.minlib.net/iii/encore/record/C__Rb3857254;jsessionid=1B6C0839D7CB4A6F5C7D69EF90A66371?lang=eng&ivts=BH7tPSggVqVS%2Bukxa4hSSw%3D%3D&casts=ihaPIPE2Iv4dH7pKbqW2ZQ%3D%3D Visit her website: https://www.maangchi.com/ Samantha writes: “Maangchi’s Big Book of Korean Cooking is a fantastic resource for people interested in Korean cuisine. Maangchi has a popular youtube channel where she shares her Korean recipes with followers all over the world. Her recipes are straightforward with enticing pictures and delicious results. I have tried a ton of her recipes, including Kimchi Stew (김치찌개), Chive Pancakes (부추전), Bibimbap (비빔밥), Pan-Fried Marinated Eggplant (가지양념구이), Garlicky Cooked Soybean Sprouts (콩나물무침), Pickled Radish for Fried Chicken (치킨무), Tteokbokki (떡볶이), and Gimbap (김밥). When I was living in South Korea, kimchi stew was one of my favorite foods. Maangchi’s Kimchi Stew is super easy to make since all you do is combine the ingredients and boil them until the pork is cooked. It is the perfect choice for a weeknight dinner when you are craving a warm, hearty stew. You need to use pork belly because the fat gives the stew flavor and prevents the pork from becoming too tough. Cooking the kimchi mellows out its flavor, making it savory instead of sour, so I highly recommend people try this dish even if they aren’t a fan of raw kimchi. Of course, this dish is also perfect for people who love kimchi. I added sliced winter melon to my stew because it has a lovely texture and absorbs the spicy flavor of the kimchi. My family enjoyed this dish so much that I made two batches and we ate it for two weeks. It reheats well in the microwave so it’s also a great choice for packed lunches. Overall, I love Maangchi’s cookbooks and I highly recommend them.” Maangchi

We are proud to follow in Haynes’ footsteps at Tennessee American Water by partnering with numerous schools to help instill an appreciation for STEM and to reach underrepresented youth. #BHM

I am so grateful for the incredible support this effort has received via donations and people signing up for consultations. Thank you SO much! Thanks to you many Ukrainian autistic kids will be able to receive sensory items and the foods that they can eat. . I have learned that families that escaped were able to take very little with them. They left all their children's sensory items at home. They do not have the money to buy these expensive items for their kids. At the same time, the kids are struggling with the trauma and the drastic change in their lives. . Children whose families stayed home in Ukraine lost access to sensory items because mostly those were available to them at their schools. Schools in Ukraine are closed now. The kids are dealing with a loss of structure and education, with anxiety and stress, and with experiencing military actions (think shelling, explosions, bomb shelters). . This fundraiser is to help them. . I have absolutely incredible news about this project that I will be announcing next week. Please follow @theexpertally to learn about the next steps for this project. . In every human disaster, people with disabilities are affected in additional ways. Autistic kids in this war struggle in many additional ways. Large charities are not set up to meet their needs. This project fills this gap for as many families as possible. Help us and watch this project grow. Donate here: https://www.theexpertally.com/ukraine-fundraising.

Affectionately named “Mr. March-on-Washington”, Bayard Rustin was one of the most influential leaders of the Civil Rights movement. Bayard Rustin’s life-long commitment to nonviolence began with his Quaker upbringing and the influence of his grandmother, whose participation in the NAACP resulted in leaders of the Black community, such as W. E. B. Du Bois and Mary McLeod Bethune, visiting the Rustin home during his childhood. Bayard Rustin served as an advisor to Rev. Dr. King during the Montgomery Bus Boycott, was a lead organizer of the March On Washington, and was integral in forming the Southern Christian Leadership Conference. He was also a labor organizer, and an organizer of youth in the fight for school integration. Despite his devotion to the Civil Rights movement, he was constantly scrutinized as a leader because he was gay and had former ties to the Communist Party. His involvement with the Communist Party ended abruptly when the chapter of the Young Communist League he was part of shifted away from the Civil Rights Movement as a key issue in 1941. As a gay man in leadership of a primarily Christian movement, Bayard Rustin often goes unmentioned. The suppression of his name in this movement was largely due to stigma against gay men, and highlights the painful decision many people with intersecting identities were (and are) forced to make when advocating for their humanity. #BlackHistoryMonth #EliminatingRacism #ywcaisonamission #YWCAKzoo ID: A black and whtie image of Bayard Rustin.

Nkechi “Kiki” James-Gillman is the principal attorney at Gillman Immigration, LLC. She knows and understands the immigrant story because she and her family have lived in many parts of the world and have found themselves navigating immigration bureaucracy for as long as she can remember. Nkechi attended Kent State University where she pursued her undergraduate degree in Business Management. After college, she moved to Washington D.C. and interned at the D.C. Superior Court, Multi-Door Dispute Resolution Center. She managed child abuse and neglect matters through the dispute resolution process. Nkechi moved to Minnesota for law school in 2006 and graduated from Hamline University School of Law in Saint Paul, Minnesota in 2009. In addition to managing her own law practice, Nkechi also serves as a pro bono attorney for the Immigrant Law Center of Minnesota, and the Volunteer Lawyers Network, representing clients in immigration matters. Most importantly, she is a fierce advocate for victims of abuse. She has zealously represented many survivors of abuse in immigration matters, under the Violence Against Women’s Act (VAWA). We are honored to have Kiki as a member of The National Black Lawyers Top 100! #ImmigrationLaw #Immigration #BlackAttorney #BlackExcellence #BlackLawFirm #BlackLawyer #BlackLawFirms #Lawyer #LawyerLife #Legal #Attorney #LawSchool #LawStudents #NationalBlackLawyers

NORTHEAST NEWSREEL NOTED PASSING Carmen Herrera, Cuban-Born Abstract Artist, Dies at 106 NEW YORK (AP) — Cuban-born artist Carmen Herrera, whose radiant color and geometric paintings were overlooked for decades before the art world took notice, has died. She was 106. Artist Antonio Bechara told The New York Times that Herrera had died at her Manhattan home Saturday. Fame finally came at age 89, when Herrera sold her first painting in 2004. It may have taken 60 years for Herrera to be discovered, but today her paintings — minimalist compositions of straight lines, form and color — are found in permanent collections of major museums including the Whitney Museum of American Art and the Museum of Modern Art in New York and the Tate Modern in London. “The core to Carmen Herrera’s painting is a drive for formal simplicity and a striking sense of color,” according to the London-based Lisson Gallery. “A master of crisp lines and contrasting chromatic planes, Herrera creates symmetry, asymmetry and an infinite variety of movement, rhythm and spatial tension across the canvas.” In 2009, the Observer of London asked, “How can we have missed these beautiful compositions?” Herrera said she painted because she had to. “It’s a compulsion that also gives me pleasure. I never in my life had any idea of money and I thought fame was a very vulgar thing. ... And at the end of my life, I’m getting a lot of recognition, to my amazement and my pleasure,” she said in a 2009 interview. Born in Havana, Cuba, in 1915, Herrera was the daughter of the founding editor of the Havana-based newspaper El Mundo and a mother who was a reporter. She studied architecture at a university in Havana, and moved frequently between Cuba and Paris during the 1930s and 1940s. She trained at the Art Students League in New York where she settled in the mid-1950s after marrying Jesse Lowenthal, a teacher of literature at Stuyvesant High School. He died in 2000. Working as a female artist in postwar America was a difficult challenge, she said. “People were not ready to receive my work,” Herrera told the Observer in 2010. She recalled how an avant-garde New York gallery owner told her bluntly, “'Carmen, you can paint circles around the men artists that I have but I’m not going to give you a show because you’re a woman.'” But being an unknown artist had its advantages, she said; it meant she could work to please herself, not someone else. In the late 2000s, she had solo exhibitions at the Museum Pfalzgalerie Kaiserslautern in Germany and the Ikon Gallery in Birmingham, England, and a decade earlier at the Museo del Barrio in New York. Herrera’s art is also found in many other museums including the Hirshhorn Museum and the Smithsonian American Art Museum in Washington, as well as the Walker Art Center in Minneapolis.

Byun Hui-su, the first known transgender soldier in South Korea, was found dead in her home on March 3. A cause of death has not been announced. In January 2020, Byun's story made international headlines when she sued the South Korean military for discharging her after she underwent gender affirmation surgery in 2019. Byun had been hoping to serve in the country's female corps, but her military reinstatement was rejected in July 2020, per the BBC. The decision to not reinstate Byun was criticized by the National Human Rights Commission of Korea. 'It was an extremely difficult decision to let my base know of my identity, but once I did, I felt much better,' Byun said in 2020. She added, 'Apart from my gender identity, I want to show everyone that I can also be one of the great soldiers who protect this country.' South Korea requires all 'able-bodied' men to serve about two years in its military. Byun's case also shed light on the ways South Korea remains largely conservative when it comes to the rights of LGBTQ+ people in the country; according to the BBC, the country has no laws preventing anti-LGBTQ+ discrimination. The announcement of Byun's death led to an outpouring of support across social media on Wednesday. She was 23.

Celebrating the contributions of the Asian American Pacific Islander community: May is Asian American Pacific Islander (AAPI) Heritage Month. Why May? The month of May was chosen to commemorate the immigration of the first Japanese to the United States on May 7, 1843, and to mark the anniversary of the completion of the transcontinental railroad on May 10, 1869. The majority of the workers who laid the tracks were Chinese immigrants. The AAPI community encompasses a diverse group, including all of the Asian continent and the Pacific Islands of Melanesia (New Guinea, New Caledonia, Vanuatu, Fiji, and the Solomon Islands), Micronesia (Marianas, Guam, Wake Island, Palau, Marshall Islands, Kiribati, Nauru, and the Federated States of Micronesia), and Polynesia (New Zealand, Hawaiian Islands, Rotuma, Midway Islands, Samoa, American Samoa, Tonga, Tuvalu, Cook Islands, French Polynesia, and Easter Island).

Today, on KYN, we are joined by Cruz Tecumseh Collin from the Lakota Nation to discuss the life of indigenous people in the contemporary world. Cruz Tecumseh Collin, commonly known as Wankatuya Keya in his native community, is one of the youngest and most active Kectil alumni. He was an outstanding colleague in the 2021 Kectil Program. Early this year, Cruz was appointed Regional Coordinator from the Lakota Nation, where he supports several Kectil Colleagues on the programme. Cruz is currently based in Toulouse, France, where he joins his mother in conducting research on the nexus between tradition and medical research. Cruz and his family are determined to preserve the beautiful history and culture of the Lakota Nation. As much as indigenous people make up only an estimated 5% of the world's population, they have different backgrounds, cultures, and traditions. They often have a shared history of being uprooted and forced from their ancestral lands. For instance, the Lakota people live in the Black Hills of South Dakota, which under an international treaty belonged to the Lakota people, but the US Government still passed a treaty to take hold of them in 1877. Listen to Cruz take Daniel through the Lakota people’s long and beautiful history, and culture as well as how they live in the broader American community today. Link to Podcast: https://bit.ly/3F3HGzh:=:https://kyn.buzzsprout.com/1834924/10445600-wankatuya-keya-from-the-native-american-community-shares-the-position-of-indigenous-community-participation-in-the-21st-centaury-world Link to all the past podcasts: https://kyn.buzzsprout.com/1834924 The Kectil Youth Network (KYN) podcast hosted by Kectil member Daniel Ochieng is a youth-run media of the Kectil Program that highlights youth from around the world to uncover the critical issues, which would not otherwise be told by the mainstream media, or might get diluted. #KYN #kectil #indigenouspeople

Songkran (สงกรานต์) is the Thai New Year that Thai people celebrated from April 13th to April 15th every year. Thai New Year marks the end of the dry season with religious ceremonies and water fights, which are a trademark of the festival. That's also celebrated in Laos, Cambodia, Myanmar, Sri Lanka, and parts of northeast India. On April 13th, the first day of the new year is known as the Song Nam Phra, where Thai people would splash the water on statues of Buddha for good luck, and it’s also the day the biggest water festival happens across the country of Thailand. สวัสดีปีใหม่ และ สุขสันต์วันสงกรานต์ กับพี่น้องชาวไทยในชุมชน North Clackamas Schools และ ในรัฐออริกัน #NCSD #Songkarn #ThaiNewYear #HappySongKran2022 #สวัสดีปีใหม่ไทย

Josh Gibson was one of the most dominant sluggers in baseball history, although racism and fate kept him from the major leagues. The former Negro Leagues star is credited with hitting almost 800 home runs over his 17-year career and was such a fearsome hitter that many fans called him the “black Babe Ruth." Gibson ultimately became the second-highest-paid player in the Negro Leagues behind another legend, Satchel Paige. Unfortunately, Gibson never got a chance to play in the majors. He died of a stroke at 35 in 1947, less than three months before Jackie Robinson made his debut for the Brooklyn Dodgers and broke the color barrier in Major League Baseball. Our people. Our stories. Mayor Foster joins governments across the country to proclaim June 19, 2022, as Juneteenth. Juneteenth commemorates Black liberation from the institution of slavery, and highlights the resilience, solidarity, and cultural Black community. Royceann Porter, Johnson County Supervisor Chair and Black Voices Project co-founder, and Nikesha Jones, Coralville Juneteenth in our Neighborhood organizer, accepted the proclamation at the June 14, 2022 City Council meeting. Johnson County Iowa Juneteenth Commemoration is hosting Juneteenth events throughout the area, including Juneteenth in our Neighborhood - Coralville, on Saturday, June 18 in S.T. Morrison Park from noon until 4:00 pm.

Black History Month is here ❤️ 💛 💚 🖤 Over the next few weeks, we will be highlighting some remarkable people of color (POC) who were raised by foster or adoptive parents and went on to leave their mark on American history. We hope these individuals' stories serve as a jumping off point for you and your family to learn more about Black history. We encourage you to reflect on the pain, the struggles, the progress, and the triumphs of our country's ongoing journey to racial equity & justice. For our interracial foster and adoptive parents, this is such an important piece to the puzzle. Join us as we celebrate the contributions of Black Americans and highlight the importance of kinship care as well as foster/adoptive parents throughout history. #BlackHistoryMonth #CelebrateBlackHistory #POC #AdoptionStory #BoDiddley #FosterCare #KinshipCare #FosterParent #Representation #SuccessStory #Koinonia

June is recognized as Men’s Mental Health Awareness Month to address specific challenges and barriers men face. Men's & boys’ mental health is an important and urgent issue in public health today. Men are 4x more likely to commit suicide than women, and are less likely to report feelings of depression or anxiety. To schedule an appointment with our Behavioral Health clinic, please call 712.722.8222 or for more information, visit https://www.siouxcenterhealth.org/services/clinics/behavioral-health/

Meet our Keynote Speaker, Elaine Dizon! 💜 ✨Elaine Dizon is a life and mindset coach, writer, mother of 2, and a recognized AT&T Business Cultural Champion. In October 2021, she won the SPARK Award – AT&T’s highest DE&I award for individuals who have made an impact towards leading efforts that build Understanding to Tolerance in the workplace. Elaine supports women in minding the mindset to nourish the next courageous conversation they are longing to have in their personal and professional spaces. As someone who believes that everyone is on a hero’s journey, Elaine is eager to support individuals in having the types of conversations that will transform their energies towards the outcomes and results they are looking for in life. Appointed Chief EntrepiNanay at Entrepinayship, Elaine supports Filipinx entrepreneurs in their personal development and business goals while caring for themselves and their families through honoring cultural crossings in life. She also serves on the advisory board of Yours Humanly, a non-profit that believes in transforming the lives of children in need around the world by providing access to quality education and equitable resources. 👉🏼 Register now at bit.ly/2022fpls:=:https://www.eventbrite.com/e/266252597687 #leadfilipino #filipinoamerican #leadershipsummit #2022flypinays #flypinays #pinay #sisterhood
